<script>
// Thanks to https://diafygi.github.io/webcrypto-examples/ and https://stackoverflow.com/q/45636545/4958

// On the face of it, JavaScript already provides an API for encryption and decryption, so it's quite simple.
// In practice, there are a few complications.
// One, the API takes an arbitrary stream of bytes (ArrayBuffer) and encrypts into another arbitrary stream of bytes.
// So as "plumbing", we need both:
// (1) turning our text-to-be-encrypted into a stream of bytes, and
// (2) turning the resulting stream of bytes into some form we'd prefer for storage.
// Something like:
// [text to be encrypted] ---> [bytes (ArrayBuffer)] ---> encrypt --> [bytes (ArrayBuffer)] --> hex,
//                    and vice-versa:
// hex --> [bytes (ArrayBuffer)] --> decrypt --> [bytes (ArrayBuffer)] --> text before encryption.

function arrayBufferFromText(text) {
    return new TextEncoder("utf-8").encode(text);
}
function textFromArrayBuffer(bytes) {
    return new TextDecoder('utf-8').decode(bytes);
}
// How do we convert an arbitrary stream of bytes to text? Maybe treat each byte (8 bits) as two hex characters.
function hexTextFromArrayBuffer(buffer) {
    const array = new Uint8Array(buffer);
    let ret = '';
    for (let c of array) {
	console.assert(0 <= c);
	console.assert(c < 256);
	let lower = (c % 16).toString(16);
	let upper = ((c - (c % 16)) / 16).toString(16);
	ret += upper;
	ret += lower;
    }
    return ret;
}
function arrayBufferFromHexText(hex) {
    let ret = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < hex.length; i += 2) {
	ret.push(parseInt(hex[i], 16) * 16 + parseInt(hex[i + 1], 16));
    }
    return Uint8Array.from(ret);
}

// To call window.crypto.subtle.encrypt(…), we need a "key" object.  This can be
// obtained through generateKey(…), or importKey(…).  As generateKey(…)  is not
// an option for us (we want to use a short user-submitted password, not a good
// long randomly generated key), we need importKey(…).

// A user-submitted password is already limited to only as much entropy as the
// user enters (e.g. a short or common password will need fewer things to
// brute-force), so good cryptographic practice is to use a key-derivation
// algorithm like PBKDF2, to at least make it "look" random (i.e. a brute-forcer
// will have to run each password being tried through this PBKDF2 first, which
// will slow them down a little -- but not magically increase the number of
// options they have to try).

async function keyFromPassword(password) {
    const importedKey = await window.crypto.subtle.importKey(
        "raw", // only "raw" is allowed
	arrayBufferFromText(password), // because it takes an ArrayBuffer of bytes
        {name: "PBKDF2"},
        false, // whether the key is extractable (i.e. can be used in exportKey)
        ["deriveKey"],
    );
    const ret = await window.crypto.subtle.deriveKey(
	{
            "name": "PBKDF2",
            salt: arrayBufferFromText('what is a salt? this stupid one: lavaNa'),
            iterations: 10000,
            hash: {name: "SHA-256"}, //can be "SHA-1", "SHA-256", "SHA-384", or "SHA-512"
	},
	importedKey, // your key from generateKey or importKey
	{ //the key type you want to create based on the derived bits
            name: "AES-GCM", //can be any AES algorithm ("AES-CTR", "AES-CBC", "AES-CMAC", "AES-GCM", "AES-CFB", "AES-KW", "ECDH", "DH", or "HMAC")
            // the generateKey parameters for that type of algorithm
            length: 256, //can be  128, 192, or 256
	},
	false, //whether the derived key is extractable (i.e. can be used in exportKey)
	["encrypt", "decrypt"] //limited to the options in that algorithm's importKey
    );
    return ret;
}

// In practice we should use a different initialization vector each time we want to encrypt.
const ivCommonBad = Uint8Array.from([45, 226, 172, 164, 203, 165, 136, 23]);

// iv = initialization vectors; don't reuse: generate a new one each type you encrypt
async function encryptString(plainTextString, password, iv) {
    iv = iv || ivCommonBad;
    const key = await keyFromPassword(password);
    const bufferToEncrypt = arrayBufferFromText(plainTextString);
    const alg = { name: "AES-GCM", iv: iv };
    const encrypted = await window.crypto.subtle.encrypt(alg, key, bufferToEncrypt);
    const ret = hexTextFromArrayBuffer(encrypted);
    // console.log('Encrypted ' + hexTextFromArrayBuffer(bufferToEncrypt) + ' to ' + ret);
    // console.log('Note that ' + ret + ' is hex text of buffer ' + arrayBufferFromHexText(ret) + ' which is ' + hexTextFromArrayBuffer(arrayBufferFromHexText(ret)));
    return ret;
};

async function decryptString(cipherHexString, password, iv) {
    iv = iv || ivCommonBad;
    const key = await keyFromPassword(password);
    const cipherBuffer = arrayBufferFromHexText(cipherHexString);
    // console.log('decrypting: ' + hexTextFromArrayBuffer(cipherBuffer));
    const alg = { name: "AES-GCM", iv: iv };
    const decrypted = await window.crypto.subtle.decrypt(alg, key, cipherBuffer);
    // console.log('Decrypted ' + cipherHexString + ' to ' + hexTextFromArrayBuffer(decrypted));
    const ret = textFromArrayBuffer(decrypted);
    return ret;
}

// We should use a different initialization vector each time we want to encrypt.
// This should just be some unique array of 12 bytes (96 bits). For convenience,
// as we already have encryptString above, we'll use it, in a really weird way.
async function makeIV(input) {
    const encrypted = await encryptString(input, 'password');
    let buf = arrayBufferFromHexText(encrypted);
    while (buf.length < 12) buf = buf + buf;
    return new Uint8Array(buf.slice(0, 11));
}

function xor(hex1, hex2) {
    const b1 = arrayBufferFromHexText(hex1);
    const b2 = arrayBufferFromHexText(hex2);
    let ret = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < b1.length && i < b2.length; ++i) {
	ret.push(b1[i] ^ b2[i]);
    }
    const x = Uint8Array.from(ret);
    return hexTextFromArrayBuffer(x);
}

/*
Try this in console:

> await encryptString('hello', 'password')
< "10b338bafa9294d620f2e6b4bee22f2e0187e2a56f"

> await decryptString('10b338bafa9294d620f2e6b4bee22f2e0187e2a56f', 'password')
< "hello"

or:

> await encryptString('hello', 'password', await makeIV('1'))
< 7bd4b50ca986571be6a53ede784c304f9e267a42f2

> await decryptString('7bd4b50ca986571be6a53ede784c304f9e267a42f2', 'password', await makeIV('1'))
< "hello"

*/
// That's it for encryption / decryption. The code actually related to this post next.
</script>

This is where you can enter some text:

<textarea id="textToEncrypt"></textarea>
<input id="encryptionNumber" type="text" value="number">
<button id="encryptButton">Encrypt</button>


<output id="encryptedTextOutput"></output>
<script>
//comment

async function decryptAll() {
    const password = document.getElementById('password').value;
    const divs = document.getElementsByClassName('encryptedOK');
    for (let div of divs) {
	const number = div.dataset.number;
	// console.log('Trying to decrypt #', div.textContent, '# with password #', password, '# and number', number);
	div.textContent = await decryptString(div.textContent, password, await makeIV(number));
	div.style.color = 'inherit';
    }
}
document.getElementById('decryptButton').addEventListener('click', decryptAll);

async function encryptInput() {
    const input = document.getElementById('textToEncrypt').value;
    const password = document.getElementById('password').value;
    const num = document.getElementById('encryptionNumber').value;
    const output = await encryptString(input, password, await makeIV(num));
    // console.log('Encrypting the text #', input, '# which is #', hexTextFromArrayBuffer(arrayBufferFromText(input)), '# gave #', output, '#');
    document.getElementById('encryptedTextOutput').value = '<div class="encryptedOK" data-number="' + num + '">' + output + '</div>';
}

document.getElementById('encryptButton').addEventListener('click', encryptInput);
</script>
